const EXTRACT_12 = `The laundrette was open twenty-four hours, which was the main thing. You could sit in there at three in the morning with the machines going and nobody would bother you. The fluorescent lights buzzed and flickered, turning everything the colour of old paper, and the air was thick with the smell of detergent and damp clothes and something underneath both of those - something human and tired and permanent, baked into the plastic chairs and the lino floor by years of people sitting and waiting and having nowhere better to be.

Jade came in most nights now. She had a routine: coins in the machine, clothes in the drum, powder from the little box she kept in her jacket pocket. She didn't always have clothes to wash. Sometimes she just put in what she was wearing, sat in the oversized hoodie she'd taken from her brother's room before she left, and watched the drum turn. It was hypnotic. The colours blurring into each other - blue, white, grey, blue, white, grey - like a tiny, contained weather system.

The old man was there again. He was always there, in the same chair by the radiator, with a newspaper he never seemed to read. He had a face like a walnut - brown and creased and hard - and hands that shook when he lifted his paper cup of coffee. He never spoke to Jade and she never spoke to him, but there was something between them - an understanding, maybe. An agreement that this place, with its humming machines and its flat light and its smell of other people's lives, was enough.

Tonight the rain was coming down hard. Jade could hear it against the plate-glass window, a constant, irregular drumming that made the laundrette feel like a boat - something small and lit, floating on a dark sea. A woman came in around two, soaked through, carrying a bin bag of clothes and a sleeping child. She didn't look at Jade. She didn't look at the old man. She just fed her coins into machine number three and sat down and closed her eyes and let out a breath that seemed to have been held for a very long time.

That was the thing about this place. Nobody pretended. Nobody smiled if they didn't mean it. Nobody asked how you were when they didn't want to know. The machines turned and the lights buzzed and the rain fell and everybody just existed, quietly, without performance, and there was a kind of grace in that.`

