const EXTRACT_13 = `The oak had been dying for three years. You could see it in the upper branches first - the way the leaves came late and fell early, the way the bark peeled in long, papery strips that collected at the base of the trunk like discarded skin. By the second summer, the crown had thinned so dramatically that sunlight fell through it in great unbroken shafts, illuminating patches of ground that had not seen direct light in a century. Bluebells appeared where none had grown before. Fox cubs played in the sudden warmth.

Martha watched it all from the kitchen window. She had bought the cottage because of the oak - because of the way it filled the garden with a green, underwater light, because of the sound the wind made moving through its thousands of leaves, a sound so layered and complex it was less like rustling than like breathing. The tree was older than the house. Older than the village. A plaque by the churchyard gate dated it to the fourteenth century, which meant it had been growing when the Black Death swept through, when Henry VIII broke with Rome, when Shakespeare was writing his plays. Six hundred years of standing in one place, pulling water from the darkness below and light from the sky above, converting both into wood and leaf and acorn with a patience that made human endeavour seem frantic and absurd.

Now the fungus was in the heartwood. The arborist had explained it gently, the way doctors explain terminal diagnoses - with carefully modulated sympathy and an undertone of professional detachment. Meripilus giganteus. Giant polypore. It entered through wounds in the bark and consumed the tree from within, breaking down the lignin that gave the wood its strength until what remained was soft, fibrous, hollow. The tree might stand for another year, perhaps two. But structurally it was already dead.

Martha placed her hand against the trunk. The bark was warm - warmer than the air, as though the tree were running a fever. Beneath her palm she could feel something: not a heartbeat, nothing so anthropomorphic, but a vibration. A deep, almost sub-audible hum. The sound of a six-hundred-year-old organism still pulling water upward through its sapwood, still photosynthesising, still doing the only thing it knew how to do. Still, in the face of everything, growing.`

