const EXTRACT_14 = `Mrs Ashworth set the teacup down and the sound it made against the saucer was the sound of something ending. She knew this. She had always known things by their sounds - the particular creak of the third stair that meant Gerald was coming up to bed, the way the letterbox snapped shut on mornings that brought bills, the different qualities of silence that filled the house at different hours: the expectant silence of early morning, the heavy silence of mid-afternoon, the silence after ten o'clock that was not really silence at all but a kind of audible emptiness, a ringing in the air where sound had been.

The house was too large for one person. Everyone said so. Her daughter Jennifer said so every Sunday on the telephone, her voice carrying that particular mixture of concern and exasperation that daughters reserve for mothers who refuse to behave sensibly. "You're rattling around in that place, Mum." Rattling. As though she were a dried seed in a pod, something desiccated and purposeless, making noise without meaning.

But Jennifer did not understand - could not understand, being only forty-three and still in the thick of life, still surrounded by noise and obligation and the daily evidence of her own necessity - that the house was not empty. It was full. Every room contained a density of accumulated experience that was almost tangible. The dining room held forty years of Sunday lunches, the slow procession of roast beef and roast lamb and roast chicken, the children growing taller in their chairs, the conversations shifting over decades from nursery chatter to adolescent silence to the strange, formal politeness of adult children visiting their parents. The bedroom held ten thousand nights. The garden held every spring.

She stood at the window and watched a blackbird on the lawn. It moved in sharp, decisive hops, cocking its head to listen for worms with an intensity of concentration she found admirable. It knew what it was doing. It had purpose. It did not stand at windows wondering how the years had managed to pass so quickly, or why the things that had once seemed permanent - health, company, the reliable functioning of one's own body - had turned out to be merely on loan.

The tea grew cold. She did not drink it. Outside, the blackbird found what it was looking for and flew away, and Mrs Ashworth watched the empty lawn and thought about nothing, or about everything, which in her experience amounted to the same thing.`

