              'Grade 6-7':
                'I agree that Mrs Ashworth\'s intelligence is central to the extract\'s emotional effect, though I would argue it is not "painful clarity" so much as a form of consciousness that cannot stop perceiving and interpreting - a curse of hyper-awareness. Her analysis of Jennifer\'s "rattling" demonstrates this: the simile "a dried seed in a pod" is not Jennifer\'s image but Mrs Ashworth\'s, generated by her own relentless interpretive faculty working against her. The taxonomy of silences - each one named and characterised - shows a mind that has spent so long alone that it has developed an expertise in absence. The third paragraph\'s counter-argument about the house being "full" is intellectually compelling but emotionally double-edged: the memories she catalogues are themselves evidence of loss, and the more vividly she recalls them, the more acutely she feels their pastness. I would complicate the statement by noting that Mrs Ashworth\'s intelligence is not purely lucid - the blackbird passage reveals a form of self-pity that her analytical mind cannot fully suppress. "It knew what it was doing. It had purpose" - the short declaratives carry an undertone of envy that is all the more affecting for being unacknowledged.',
