              'Grade 4-5':
                'The writer represents Ryan\'s thoughts by using very long sentences that run into each other without full stops. This makes it feel like we are inside his head, hearing his thoughts as they happen. He jumps between different ideas - the rain, his hands, the woman on the phone, a pigeon - which shows that his mind wanders from one thing to another. The informal language, like "which had genuinely blown his mind," makes Ryan sound like a real teenager. The lack of capital letters at the start of paragraphs is unusual and makes the writing feel like a continuous flow of thought.',
              'Grade 6-7':
                'The writer employs stream-of-consciousness technique to replicate the associative, non-hierarchical nature of adolescent thought. The absence of conventional punctuation - no full stops within paragraphs, no capitalisation at paragraph openings - removes the structural markers that normally organise prose, forcing the reader to experience Ryan\'s world as an undifferentiated flow. The sentence structure mirrors cognitive process: "he\'d noticed for the first time that they were his father\'s hands the same square fingers the same flat nails bitten down to nothing" accumulates details through asyndetic listing, each observation triggering the next without conscious selection. The transitions between topics are achieved through spatial proximity rather than logical connection: the woman "next to him" triggers reflection on communication; the pigeon landing triggers reflection on evolution. The colloquial register - "genuinely blown his mind," "isn\'t it" - grounds the writing in an authentic teenage voice, while the philosophical observations ("that\'s what people do... they make sounds at each other to prove they\'re still here") reveal a depth of perception that the casual register almost conceals. The lie to Leah ("on the bus") is structurally significant: it is the only moment where Ryan performs rather than simply perceives, and its dishonesty highlights the authenticity of everything surrounding it.',
