              'Grade 6-7':
                'I largely agree, though I would frame the achievement differently: rather than transforming the ordinary into the extraordinary, the writer reveals the extraordinary that already exists within the ordinary - and the distinction matters. The extract\'s formal innovation is central to this effect: by removing conventional punctuation and allowing thought to flow without hierarchical interruption, the writer insists that every perception has equal claim to attention. The pigeon meditation is the clearest example: "you look at a pigeon and you see nothing you see grey and ordinary and forgettable" articulates the default perception before dismantling it - "but actually what you\'re looking at is sixty-five million years of survival." The shift from "you see" to "what you\'re looking at" is linguistically precise: seeing is passive, looking is active, and the extract argues for the latter. However, I would qualify the claim that "the reader sees the world differently": what the extract achieves is more specific than general revelation. It demonstrates a mode of attention - sustained, associative, non-judgemental - and invites the reader to adopt it temporarily. Whether this persists beyond the reading experience is another question.',
